paragraph_text = "Teaching the player how to play game can be accomplished in many ways. Use short labels in unintrusive spots to teach a new mechanic. Gently flash an object in the environment to lure to player to something good, or flash something regurarly to indicate a hazard. Replicating control schemes from other popular games that belong in the same genre can also help."

[node name="SlideParagraphElement2" parent="." index="3" instance=ExtResource( 2 )]
margin_top = 360.0
margin_right = 1920.0
margin_bottom = 529.0
rect_min_size = Vector2( 0, 169 )
paragraph_text = "Those are only some of many possibilities, but even so these seemingly small design decisions can lead to a more intuitive experience. Study other games that are known amongst others and try to understand how they teach the player. Sometimes, certain gameplay elements can be even tought with just gameplay alone."

[node name="SlideParagraphElement3" parent="." index="4" instance=ExtResource( 2 )]
margin_top = 577.0
margin_right = 1920.0
margin_bottom = 703.0
rect_min_size = Vector2( 0, 126 )
paragraph_text = "It is also a good idea to splice the tutorial into segments and put them between chunks of real gameplay. This allows for the player to digest new information whilst leaving new mechanics for later to keep the game fresh."
